Loading Data

Replace local file with URL for easier access. Instead of Auto=read.table("Auto.data") you will use:

Auto=read.table("https://raw.githubusercontent.com/ValeriaSalinasLopez/ValeriaSalinasLopez.github.io/master/Data/Auto.data")

When you view the data table, the first row is occupied by the variable names. We need to tidy up our data. To do so you could use fix(Auto), but it is not efficient. Instead use the following code:

Auto=read.table("https://raw.githubusercontent.com/ValeriaSalinasLopez/ValeriaSalinasLopez.github.io/master/Data/Auto.data",header=T,na.strings="?")

You can read in any data file the same way by using the URL from the raw data in GitHub. Again, dim() will tell you the number of rows/observations and columns/variables in the data.

Locating Specific Data

As shown before, you can request for specific observations to be displayed with the code Auto[1:4,], however, the ouput will not look too great. With the following code, a table will be generated.

knitr::kable(
  Auto[1:4, ], 
  caption = "Observations 1 through 4"
)

You can eliminate observations that have missing values by using:

Auto=na.omit(Auto)

Additional Graphical and Numerical Summaries

You cannot simply state a variable to use in a plot without referencing the dataset first. Therefore using plot(cylinders, mpg) would result in an error message.

plot(Auto$cylinders, Auto$mpg)

#### You could use attach(Auto) before creating the plot to use the varibale names alone. The function as.factor() will convert the numeric varaibale “cylinders” into a factor to analyze the variable in terms of levels, making the above plot easier to interpret.

attach(Auto)
cylinders=as.factor(cylinders)
plot(cylinders, mpg)

There are many commands available to change the graph’s color, variable width, position, and labels. As shown by the four different graphs.

plot(cylinders, mpg, col="red")

plot(cylinders, mpg, col="red", varwidth=T)

plot(cylinders, mpg, col="red", varwidth=T,horizontal=T)

plot(cylinders, mpg, col="red", varwidth=T, xlab="cylinders", ylab="MPG")

#### Histogram

hist(mpg)

hist(mpg,col=2)

hist(mpg,col=2,breaks=15)

#### The pairs() function is used to make a graph matrix, but the function looks for numeric and continuous variables to using pairs(Auto) will not work. Instead you must input the specific varibales you want from a specified dataset.

pairs(~ mpg + displacement + horsepower + weight + acceleration, Auto)

#### The identify() function allows you to click on specific points on a graph to be labelled.

plot(horsepower,mpg)
identify(horsepower,mpg,name)

Non-linear Transformations of the Predictors

lm() can be cubed or logged.

lm.fit2=lm(medv~lstat+I(lstat^2))
summary(lm.fit2)

Terms in the formula raised to a power with ^ must be wrapped inside a call to I() to prevent interpretation and treated as is.

Writing Functions

We can create a function that will do multiple commands at once. Here we will create a funciton that will load the “ISLR” and “MASS” packages simultaneaously.

LoadLibraries=function(){
 library(ISLR)
 library(MASS)
 print("The libraries have been loaded.")
 }

To load the libraries, you now can just use this function:

LoadLibraries()
## [1] "The libraries have been loaded."
